Coding Project Proposal: Manager Equipment Collection Portal
1) Project Overview
Goal
Build a lightweight, manager-facing web UI that shows managers the equipment assigned to their direct/indirect reports and lets managers mark items as “received/collected.” When an item is marked collected, the system alerts IT and creates a collection log so pickups/returns can be tracked and formally closed out. This is a “last mile logistics” tool to prevent equipment from being left with departing staff and to ensure collection accountability.
Strategy
Front-end first: deliver usable prototypes quickly, then wire into live systems via environment variables and documented APIs. Use Active Directory / Entra’s manager field to determine who a manager can view.
Pilot
Prototype for ~1–2 weeks, review usability and collaboration, then expand scope if successful.

2) Scope and Core Requirements
A) Manager UI (Web App)
Show a staff list scoped to the authenticated manager (including indirect reports if enabled).
Show equipment assigned per staff member (from ref tab data).
Allow manager action: Mark as “Collected/Received” (with timestamp and optional notes).
Enforce visibility rules based on AD/Entra manager hierarchy (no cross-team visibility).
B) Alerts to IT
When a manager marks an item collected:
Create a collection event record in the database
Notify IT via a configurable channel (Email / Teams / webhook)
C) Data & Logging
Persist AD/Entra-derived user records (employee identifier, manager relationships, etc.) in DB for fast lookup.
Maintain collection logs:
Collection event history (who marked it, when, notes)
“Close out” state once IT has physically recovered the item (pickup/received by IT)
D) Integration & Deployment
Integrate with ref tab API for equipment assignment records.
Deploy via GitHub → Coolify/Nixpacks, with environment variables supplying secrets/API keys.
App framework suggestion: Next.js (fast UI prototyping, API routes, auth-friendly).

3) Technical Approach
Authentication & Authorization
Use organization SSO where feasible (or a pilot-friendly auth approach), then:
Identify the current user
Resolve that user’s direct/indirect reports from AD/Entra data
Restrict all queries/results to that scope
Manager Hierarchy Resolution
Primary mechanism: AD/Entra manager attribute
Store a normalized representation in DB:
users table with manager pointers
Optional cached hierarchy/closure table for faster “indirect reports” queries
Data Flow
Manager opens portal → authenticates
App queries DB for manager’s org scope (staff list)
App fetches equipment for staff from ref tab (directly or via caching layer)
Manager marks item collected → app writes collection record → triggers IT notification
IT marks item closed out when pickup is complete

4) System Components
Front-end
Next.js UI pages:
Manager dashboard (staff list + equipment summaries)
Staff detail view (equipment list + status)
Collection history / activity feed (optional in pilot)
Backend (API layer)
Next.js API routes or separate lightweight service
Endpoints for:
staff scope retrieval
equipment retrieval (ref tab proxy)
collection action logging
close out actions (IT role)
Database
Stores:
AD/Entra user + manager relationships
Equipment references (optional cache)
Collection logs + close out status
Notifications
Configurable notification provider:
Email (SMTP/O365), Teams webhook, or n8n webhook
Pilot can start with the simplest reliable channel

